06019nam a22007815i 9780824878054DE-B159720210729020517.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210729t20192019hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248780547 a10.1515/97808248780542doi  a(DE-B1597)513354  a(OCoLC)1098213512  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 7aREL0070502bisacsh0484pa290qDE-1011 aCaple, Jane E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMorality and Monastic Revival in Post-Mao Tibet /cJane E. Caple; ed. by Mark Michael Rowe. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2019] 4cÂ©2019  a1 online resource (232 p.) :b9 b&w illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aContemporary Buddhism00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tSeries Editor's Preface -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes on Romanization and Naming Practices -- tIntroduction. Negotiating Moral Boundaries -- t1. Monastic Revival. A Social and Moral Reordering -- t2. Monastic Reform. The Path to "Self-Sufficiency" -- t3. Monastic Tourism. Defining Value -- t4. Monastic Development in Morally Troubled Times -- t5. Monastic Recruitment and Retention -- t6. The Future of Mass Monasticism -- t7. Seeing beyond the State -- tCoda -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe speed and extent of the Tibetan Buddhist monastic revival make it one of the most extraordinary stories of religious resurgence in post-Mao China. At the end of the 1970s, there were no working monasteries; within a decade, thousands had been reconstructed and repopulated. Most studies have focused on the political challenges facing Tibetan monasteries, emphasizing their relationship to the Chinese state. Yet, in their efforts to revive and develop their institutions, monks have also had to negotiate a rapidly changing society, playing a delicate balancing act fraught with moral dilemma as well as political danger. Drawing on the recent "moral turn" in anthropology, this volume, the first full-length ethnographic study of the subject, explores the social and moral dimensions of monastic revival and reform across a range of Geluk monasteries in northeast Tibet (Amdo/Qinghai province) from the 1980s on. Author Jane Caple's analysis shows that ideas and debates about how best to maintain the mundane bases of monastic Buddhism-economy and population-are intermeshed with those concerning the proper role and conduct of monks and the ethics of monastic-lay relations. Facing a shrinking monastic population, monks are grappling with the impacts of secular education, demographic transition, rising living standards, urbanization, and marketization, all of which have driven debates within Buddhism elsewhere and fueled perceptions of monastic decline. Some Tibetans-including monks-are even questioning the "good" of the mass form of monasticism that has been a distinctive feature of Tibetan society for hundreds of years. Given monastic Buddhism's integral position in Tibetan community life and association with Tibetan identity, Caple argues that its precarity in relation to Tibetan society raises questions about its future that go well beyond the issue of religious freedom.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aBuddhist monasterieszChinazTibet Autonomous Region. 0aDge-lugs-pa (Sect)zChinazTibet Autonomous RegionxCustoms and practices. 0aMonastic and religious life (Buddhism)zChinazTibet Autonomous Region. 7aRELIGION / Buddhism / Tibetan.2bisacsh1 aRowe, Mark Michael, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2019z978311071956708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKA